<li role="presentation"><a href='?term="Shoulder%20Elbow"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem" data-add-to-search="true">Add to search</a></li>
</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>
<em>Cutibacterium acnes</em> is less commonly identified by next-generation sequencing than culture in primary shoulder surgery</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Namdari%20S"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Surena Namdari</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3><span class="name western">Surena Namdari</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Institute, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Namdari%20S"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Surena Namdari</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>✉</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Nicholson%20T"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Thema Nicholson</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3><span class="name western">Thema Nicholson</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Institute, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Nicholson%20T"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Thema Nicholson</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Abboud%20J"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id3"><span class="name western">Joseph Abboud</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id3">
<h3><span class="name western">Joseph Abboud</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Institute, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Abboud%20J"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Joseph Abboud</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Lazarus%20M"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id4"><span class="name western">Mark Lazarus</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id4">
<h3><span class="name western">Mark Lazarus</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Institute, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Lazarus%20M"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Mark Lazarus</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ramsey%20ML"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id5"><span class="name western">Matthew L Ramsey</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id5">
<h3><span class="name western">Matthew L Ramsey</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Institute, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ramsey%20ML"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Matthew L Ramsey</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Williams%20G"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id6"><span class="name western">Gerald Williams</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id6">
<h3><span class="name western">Gerald Williams</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Institute, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Williams%20G"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Gerald Williams</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Parvizi%20J"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id7"><span class="name western">Javad Parvizi</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id7">
<h3><span class="name western">Javad Parvizi</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Institute, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Parvizi%20J"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Javad Parvizi</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="aff1-1758573219842160">
<sup>1</sup>Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Institute, Thomas Jefferson University, Philadelphia, PA, USA</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="corresp1-1758573219842160">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline">Surena Namdari, Department of Orthopaedic Surgery, Rothman Institute, Thomas Jefferson University, 925 Chestnut Steet, 5th Floor, Philadelphia, PA 19107, USA. Email: <span>surena.namdari@rothmaninstitute.com</span></p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Received 2018 Nov 28; Revised 2019 Mar 9; Accepted 2019 Mar 13; Issue date 2020 Jun.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div>© 2019 The British Elbow &amp; Shoulder Society</div>
<div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC7285974  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32565918/" class="usa-link">32565918</a>
</div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="abstract1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<section id="sec1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h3>
<p>High rates of positive <em>Cutibacterium acnes</em> cultures from primary shoulder surgery make positive cultures in the revision surgery setting difficult to interpret. Our goal was to determine concordance between culture and next-generation sequencing techniques for identification of <em>C. acnes</em> from primary shoulder surgery.</p></section><section id="sec2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods</h3>
<p>Patients undergoing shoulder arthroscopy for rotator cuff tear or primary anatomic shoulder arthroplasty for osteoarthritis were prospectively enrolled. Specimens were sent for culture (aerobic and anaerobic) and next-generation sequencing. For next-generation sequencing, the entire microbial DNA was sequenced in order to identify pathogens within the sample.</p></section><section id="sec3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h3>
<p>Our cohort consisted of 90 patients (45 patients in the osteoarthritis group and 45 patients in the rotator cuff tear group). At least one sample was positive for <em>C. acnes</em> in 18 (20%) cases by culture and in 14 (15.6%) cases by next-generation sequencing (p = 0.559). Four (22.2%) of the 18 cases with positive <em>C. acnes</em> cultures also had <em>C. acnes</em> identified by next-generation sequencing (kappa = 0.238). There was no difference in <em>C. acnes</em> identification rates between osteoarthritis and rotator cuff tear groups.</p></section><section id="sec4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusions</h3>
<p>There was limited concordance between culture and next-generation sequencing for <em>C. acnes</em> identification. Further studies are needed to determine the potential for next-generation sequencing as a diagnostic tool.</p></section><section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> next-generation sequencing, <em>Propionibacterium acnes</em>, <em>Cutibacterium acnes</em>, culture, primary shoulder surgery</p></section></section><section id="sec1-1758573219842160"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h2>
<p><em>Cutibacterium acnes</em> is frequently cultured in patients with infections after open and arthroscopic shoulder surgery<sup><a href="#bibr1-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr1-1758573219842160">1</a>–<a href="#bibr4-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr4-1758573219842160">4</a></sup> and is thought to be the most common cause of postoperative shoulder infection. Before the significance of positive <em>C. acnes</em> cultures in the setting of revision surgery can be determined, the role of <em>C. acnes</em> as a commensal organism, infecting agent, or initiator of joint degeneration in the native joint must be understood. A major stumbling block to this understanding comes from the difficulties in culturing <em>C. acnes</em>. It is likely that all cultures either underestimate (due to its indolent nature) or overestimate (due to contamination or deep tissue inoculation) the true incidence of <em>C. acnes</em> in the shoulder. Sethi et al. have reported 20%–30% detection rates of <em>C. acnes</em> from the glenohumeral joint in patients undergoing primary arthroscopic surgery and suggest that this may be a result of persistent skin contamination even after skin preparation.<sup><a href="#bibr5-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr5-1758573219842160">5</a></sup> Similarly, studies in male patients have reported 60%–70% rates of positive dermal punch biopsies for <em>C. acnes</em> after skin preparation.<sup><a href="#bibr6-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr6-1758573219842160">6</a>,<a href="#bibr7-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr7-1758573219842160">7</a></sup></p>
<p>Next-generation sequencing (NGS) is a molecular technique that sequences the entire microbial DNA and identifies the pathogens within a sample. NGS has been shown to identify pathogens in patients with neurological infections and systemic sepsis.<sup><a href="#bibr8-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr8-1758573219842160">8</a>,<a href="#bibr9-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr9-1758573219842160">9</a></sup> It is unknown whether NGS may play a role in the diagnostic algorithm of <em>C. acnes</em> shoulder infections. The purpose of this study was to determine whether standard culture techniques and NGS yield similar results for <em>C. acnes</em> identification in cases of primary shoulder surgery.</p></section><section id="sec2-1758573219842160"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods</h2>
<p>Following approval from the institutional review board, a consecutive series of patients (&gt;18 years of age) undergoing shoulder arthroscopy for rotator cuff tear (RCT) or undergoing primary anatomic shoulder arthroplasty for osteoarthritis (OA) were prospectively enrolled. Patients who took antibiotics in the preceding month; patients with psoriatic/eczematous or other lesions on the shoulder girdle; those who had undergone previous shoulder surgery (open or arthroscopic); or patients with a history of joint infection, osteomyelitis, or sepsis were excluded. Patients were followed for 90 days after surgery to determine whether clinical signs of infection developed.</p>
<section id="sec3-1758573219842160"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Surgical site preparation</h3>
<p>Prior to surgery, hair in the shoulder girdle was routinely removed with a battery-powered clipper in the preoperative area. The shoulder was then wiped using a 2% chlorhexadine gluconate cloth (Sage Products, Cary, IL). All patients received standard preoperative antibiotics (weight-based cefazolin or clindamycin in patients with a cephalosporin allergy) within 1 h of incision. The shoulder, axilla, and entire upper extremity were then pre-scrubbed with a sponge saturated with a 7.5% providone–iodine solution (Betadine Surgical Scrub; Purdue Pharma, Stamford, CT) and were wiped clean with a sterile towel. The shoulder, axilla, and arm were then prepared with two 26-ml applicators containing a 2% chlorhexidine gluconate and 70% isopropyl alcohol formulation (ChloraPrep; Cardinal Health, Dublin, OH). The shoulder was then draped in a standard sterile manner.</p></section><section id="sec4-1758573219842160"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Sample acquisition</h3>
<section id="sec5-1758573219842160"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">RCT group</h4>
<p>The arthroscope was inserted into the joint through a posterior arthroscopic portal. Upon removing the trocar, synovial egressing fluid was collected. If fluid was not obtained, the scope was first introduced without turning on fluid. A spinal needle was inserted through the anterior portal under visualization and directed towards synovial fluid. If fluid was present, a 10-cc syringe was attached to the spinal needle and fluid was attempted to be aspirated. In this study, a minimum of 2 cc of synovial fluid was needed for sample processing. After fluid was turned on and an anterior cannula was placed, tissue specimens were taken from the rotator interval, the superior capsule, and the inferior capsule using “fresh” instruments. Immediately following collection in the operating room, orthopedic fluids and tissues were placed into sterile containers and transferred to the institution’s microbiology laboratory for culture. One specimen from each location was also sent for NGS.</p></section><section id="sec6-1758573219842160"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">OA group</h4>
<p>Following deltopectoral exposure, a spinal need needle attached to a 10-cc syringe was inserted through the rotator interval and synovial fluid was aspirated. In this study, a minimum of 2 cc of synovial fluid was needed for sample processing. The glenohumeral joint was then accessed by opening the rotator interval and performing a lesser tuberosity osteotomy. Once the joint was opened, tissue specimens were taken from the rotator interval, superior capsule, and inferior capsule using “fresh” instruments. Immediately following collection in the operating room, synovial fluid and tissue samples were placed into sterile containers and transferred to the institution’s microbiology laboratory. One specimen from each location was also sent for NGS analysis (MicroGen Dx, Lubbock, TX).</p></section><section id="sec7-1758573219842160"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">Culture protocol</h4>
<p>Specimens were homogenized with 1 ml of liquid thioglycollate medium to create a thick paste. The homogenate was then inoculated onto aerobic blood agar plate, chocolate agar plate, MacConkey agar plates, anaerobic blood agar plates, thioglycollate broth, and one drop was placed onto a glass gram stain slide. The plates were allowed to incubate for 48 h before removing them from the chamber and examining them for growth. If the thioglycollate broth was cloudy and there were organisms observed on the original gram stain which did not grow on plated media, it was subcultured on the agar plates described above. Each plate was examined every other day for the first week and then on days 7 and 13 or until positive.</p></section><section id="sec8-1758573219842160"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">NGS analysis</h4>
<p>Upon arrival at the laboratory, the first step was DNA extraction and performance of a quantitative polymerase chain reaction (PCR) to determine the bacterial burden present in the sample. The second step was the NGS assay. Initially, the DNA was amplified via a PCR reaction using forward and reverse primers flanking the region of interest. For the detection of bacterial and fungal species, the two regions of interest were the 16 S and internal transcribed spacer, which were highly conserved regions of the rRNA gene in bacteria and fungi, respectively.<sup><a href="#bibr10-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr10-1758573219842160">10</a>,<a href="#bibr11-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr11-1758573219842160">11</a></sup> Following the amplification process, the amplified DNA was then pooled based on amplification strength. Sample DNA was then loaded onto beads for the emulsion PCR. Emulsion PCR was then carried out to generate high levels of the sample DNA for NGS. The sample was then sequenced on the Ion Torrent personal genome machine sequencing platform (ThermoFisher Scientific, Waltham, MA). The Ion Torrent sequencer relied on the principle that a hydrogen ion was released each time a nucleotide was incorporated into the DNA, thus generating a change in pH. This change in pH corresponded to the number of nucleotides incorporated into the growing sequence, which was then detected by the sequencer. The final step before data analysis consisted of denoising to remove short sequences that could interfere with the interpretation of the data generated.<sup><a href="#bibr12-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr12-1758573219842160">12</a></sup> The sequence reads generated were then compared against a curated National Institute of Health/Genbank database. The comparison against the database was performed using USearch7,<sup><a href="#bibr13-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr13-1758573219842160">13</a></sup> and an agreement of at least 90% between the sequence reads and the database was necessary.</p></section></section><section id="sec9-1758573219842160"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Statistical analysis</h3>
<p>On the basis of the assumption that a 35% difference in the positive culture rate between techniques would be clinically significant, the number of patients required to achieve 80% power at an alpha = 0.05 was 37 patients per group. Comparative statistics between groups were performed using Mann–Whitney tests for continuous variables and Fisher’s exact test for non-continuous variables.</p></section></section><section id="sec10-1758573219842160"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h2>
<p>There were 45 patients in the OA group and 45 patients in the RCT group. The OA group was significantly older in age than the RCT group (65.8 ± 10.3 vs. 60.2 ± 7.4, p = 0.004). The OA group and the RCT groups were similar with regard to gender (23 males vs. 23 males, p = 1.0) and body mass index (30.9 ± 6.6 kg/m<sup>2</sup> vs. 31.6 ± 6.7 kg/m<sup>2</sup>, p = 0.61). There were no cases of clinical infection within 90 days of surgery in either group.</p>
<section id="sec11-1758573219842160"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Overall cohort</h3>
<p>In the overall cohort, at least one sample was positive for <em>C. acnes</em> in 18 (20%) cases by culture and in 14 (15.6%) cases by NGS (p = 0.559). Eight patients had &gt;2 positive cultures for <em>C. acnes</em> and seven patients had &gt;2 positive samples that identified <em>C. acnes</em> by NGS (p = 1.0). Only 4 (22.2%) of the 18 cases with positive <em>C. acnes</em> cultures also had <em>C. acnes</em> identified by NGS (kappa = 0.238).</p></section><section id="sec12-1758573219842160"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">OA vs. RCT groups cultures</h3>
<p>Ten (22.2%) patients in the OA group and 8 (17.8%) patients in the RCT group had at least one positive <em>C. acnes</em> culture (p = 0.79) (<a href="#table1-1758573219842160" class="usa-link">Tables 1</a> and <a href="#table2-1758573219842160" class="usa-link">2</a>). Four patients in each group had &gt;2 positive cultures for <em>C. acnes</em> (p = 1.00). One patient in the OA group had a single positive sample for <em>Staphylococcus epidermidis</em>, and no other organisms were identified in the RCT group. The mean time to isolate <em>C. acnes</em> by culture was 6.5 (±1.4) days (range 5–8 days) in the OA group and 6.4 (±1.1) days (range 5–8 days) in the RCT group (p = 0.83). Thirty-two (71.1%) cases from the OA group and 13 (28.9%) cases from the RCT group had sufficient synovial fluid for culture analysis. None of the synovial fluid samples from the OA group and one of the synovial fluid samples from the RCT group isolated <em>C. acnes</em> (p = 0.29).

</p>
