<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/table2-1758573219842160/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<div class="tw-foot p"><div class="fn" id="table-fn2-1758573219842160"><p>NGS: next-generation sequencing.</p></div></div></section></section><section id="sec13-1758573219842160"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">OA vs. RCT groups NGS</h3>
<p>Organisms were identified by NGS in 6 (13.3%) patients in the RCT group and in 15 (33.3%) patients in the OA group (p = 0.05) (<a href="#table1-1758573219842160" class="usa-link">Tables 1</a> and <a href="#table2-1758573219842160" class="usa-link">2</a>). All samples in which organisms were identified were polymicrobial ranging from 3 to 11 identified bacteria. Eleven (24.4%) patients in the OA group and three (6.7%) patients in the RCT group had at least one positive <em>C. acnes</em> sample (p = 0.039). Five patients in the OA group and two patients in the RCT group had &gt;2 samples in which <em>C. acnes</em> was identified (p = 0.434). One of the 32 (3.1%) cases from the OA group (one specimen: <em>S. epidermidis</em>; <em>C. acnes</em>; <em>Acinetobacter radioresistens</em>) and none of the cases from the RCT group that had sufficient synovial fluid for analysis identified bacteria.</p></section></section><section id="sec14-1758573219842160"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Discussion</h2>
<p>Because of the high rates of positive <em>C. acnes</em> cultures in primary shoulder surgery, positive cultures in the revision setting can be difficult to interpret. In this study, we show limited concordance between culture and NGS for identification of <em>C. acnes</em> in primary shoulder surgery. Additionally, we report a similar rate of <em>C. acnes</em> identification in cases of OA and RCT by culture and NGS.</p>
<p><em>C. acnes</em> has been a notoriously difficult microbe to identify. Because of this, researchers have recommended prolonged culture incubation times and use of both aerobic and anaerobic mediums to improve culture isolation rates.<sup><a href="#bibr14-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr14-1758573219842160">14</a></sup> With increased vigilance and greater emphasis on <em>C. acnes</em> identification, positive culture rates in revision shoulder surgery have been reported as high as 56%.<sup><a href="#bibr4-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr4-1758573219842160">4</a></sup> While this is concerning, the impact of such high rates of positive cultures must be considered within the context of positive cultures during primary shoulder arthroscopy also reported to be as high as 56%.<sup><a href="#bibr5-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr5-1758573219842160">5</a></sup> We demonstrated an approximately 20% rate of <em>C. acnes</em> identification by culture in both primary arthroscopic shoulder surgery and primary open shoulder surgery.</p>
<p>NGS permits the generation of thousands of individual sequences from a single broad-range PCR. This provides comprehensive information on the organisms within a sample. Previous studies using PCR-based assays have been criticized for an inability to distinguish between live and dead DNA and for identifying organisms in cases presumed to be aseptic, leading to concern for high false-positive rates. In this study, NGS identified bacteria in 23% of all cases and all of these cases were polymicrobial. It is certainly possible that identified bacteria represent the microbiome in some shoulders and are unlikely to cause true infection. The true bacterial microbiome of the native shoulder and the non-pathogenic bacterial loads of organisms that are commensal to the joint are unknown. This study would indicate that the shoulder microbiome includes <em>C. acnes</em> and a number of other bacterial species that are not commonly identified by culture and are of unknown significance. Since our culture strategies (media used, length of incubation, and vigilance of microbiology laboratory) in shoulder surgery are purposefully geared towards identifying <em>C. acnes</em>, it is possible that this one species of the microbiome is preferentially identified in culture analysis even though its role may not be pathogenic.</p>
<p>Because of the lack of concordance between the two tests, our study raises questions regarding the reliability of both culture and NGS for identification of <em>C. acnes</em> in the setting of primary shoulder surgery. In almost four-fifths of those cases with positive cultures for <em>C. acnes</em>, NGS did not identify the organism. There are two potential explanations for this finding. One explanation is that cultures are more prone than NGS to false-positive results from inoculation of deep tissues with <em>C. acnes</em> organisms from the skin, from contamination from the air, or from frank contamination in the laboratory. Given that only 22% of the cases with positive <em>C. acnes</em> cultures also had <em>C. acnes</em> identified by NGS, this explanation would also lead to the hypothesis that cultures miss cases of “true positives” and may raise concerns regarding the accuracy of our current methods of identifying bacteria and defining infection in the shoulder joint. Another explanation is that NGS is a poor tool for <em>C. acnes</em> identification, demonstrating a higher false-negative rate than cultures and is less accurate than cultures because many of the cases in which <em>C. acnes</em> was identified by culture were not the same cases in which <em>C. acnes</em> was identified by NGS. This explanation would hypothesize a limited role for NGS is the diagnostic algorithm for infection. This study was not designed to determine the role of NGS in the diagnostic algorithm of shoulder prosthetic joint infection but serves as a first step towards investigating its utility.</p>
<p>Levy et al. performed a prospective investigation of <em>C. acnes</em> identification in patients with shoulder OA undergoing primary shoulder arthroplasty.<sup><a href="#bibr15-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr15-1758573219842160">15</a></sup> In this study, the authors took substantial care to avoid mishandling and contamination of specimens, used both aerobic and anaerobic media, and held cultures for two weeks.<sup><a href="#bibr15-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr15-1758573219842160">15</a></sup> In 41.8% of the 55 cases, <em>C. acnes</em> was found in the joint fluid and tissues samples. The authors hypothesized that <em>C. acnes</em> may be involved in the pathogenesis of glenohumeral OA in the same way that <em>Helicobacter pylori</em> is believed to be an initiator for the development of gastric ulcers.<sup><a href="#bibr16-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr16-1758573219842160">16</a>,<a href="#bibr17-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr17-1758573219842160">17</a></sup> It would appear that, if <em>C. acnes</em> was to be implicated as an etiological factor in OA of the shoulder, a significantly larger number of patients with OA would have a positive culture for <em>C. acnes</em> than the 22% observed in this study.</p>
<p>This study has some shortfalls, and the data need to be interpreted with these limitations in mind. The two methods for culture acquisition were different given the arthroscopic and open approaches. Because of this, there could certainly be a concern for an increase in the false-positive rates with open surgery due to a greater risk of contamination; and so, it is not possible to disprove the hypothesis that <em>C. acnes</em> is an initiator of glenohumeral OA. It is possible that there is a true difference between the two groups but, with secondary contamination through the skin incision, this difference was camouflaged. Additionally, an adequate amount of synovial fluid required for NGS testing was not commonly obtained in RCT patients and may be a result of the pathology creating less synovial fluid or a result of our sampling method. We did not include a negative control in this study; however, a recent study from our institution has reported a 20% false-positive <em>C. acnes</em> rate in negative controls.<sup><a href="#bibr7-1758573219842160" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="bibr7-1758573219842160">7</a></sup> NGS was used as a research tool in this study and the cost-effectiveness of using this testing modality in clinical practice remains to be determined. Finally, though there were no cases of clinical infection during the first 90 days after surgery, it is possible that prolonged clinical follow-up could demonstrate differences in infection rates.</p>
<p>Cultures are the traditional gold standard for the diagnosis of infection; however, the poor agreement between cultures and NGS raises questions regarding the accuracy of our current methods of identifying <em>C. acnes</em>. There appear to be many different bacterial species that comprise the microbiome of the native shoulder. Further study will be necessary to better define the shoulder microbiome, to confirm the accuracy of cultures for <em>C. acnes</em> identification, and to determine whether NGS has a role in the diagnosis of <em>C. acnes</em> infections.</p></section><section id="sec19-1758573219842160"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Declaration of Conflicting Interests</h2>
<p>The author(s) declared no potential conflicts of interest with respect to the research, authorship, and/or publication of this article.</p></section><section id="sec20-1758573219842160"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Funding</h2>
